efetch() macro does wonders for the rest.<br /><br />prefetching and friends won't do _anything_ for the case of a cache line<br />bouncing back and forth between CPU's.<br /><br />In fact, it can easily make things _worse_, simply by having bouncing<br />happen even more (you bounce it into the CPU for the prefetch, another CPU<br />bounces it back, and you bounce it in again for the actual lock).<br /><br />And this isn't at all unlikely if you have a lock that is accessed a _lot_<br />but held only for short times.<br /><br />Now, I'm not convinced that pagecache_lock is _that_ critical yet, but is<br />it one of the top ones? Definitely.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.kernel.org<br />More majordomo info at  <a href="http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html">http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html</a><br />Please read the FAQ at  <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
